fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let (X,\mathscr {O}_X) be a ringed space, \mathscr {F} a sheaf of \mathscr {O}_X-modules, and \mathscr {G} a subsheaf of \mathscr {F}.
      If \mathscr {F} is coherent, then the following conditions are equivalent:


\mathscr {G} is coherent;

\mathscr {G} is of finite presentation;

\mathscr {G} is of finite type.

We know that, in general, coherence implies finite presentation implies finite type, so we know that [(1) \implies  (2) \implies  (3)] even without the hypothesis that \mathscr {F} is coherent.
        But then, since \mathscr {F} is coherent, [(3) \implies  (2)].
        Finally, we have a sort of domino effect: if \mathscr {H} is a subsheaf of \mathscr {G}, then it is also a subsheaf of \mathscr {F}, and the property of being finite type is a property on a sheaf itself, not on its realisation as a subsheaf of a specific sheaf;
        in other words, any subsheaf \mathscr {H} of \mathscr {G} of finite type is also a subsheaf of \mathscr {F} of finite type, and thus of finite presentation (since \mathscr {F} is coherent);
        thus \mathscr {G} is coherent, i.e. [(2) \implies  (1)].
